The problem involves finding the probability of at least one match when drawing balls from an urn with \(n\) balls numbered 1 to \(n\) without replacement, where a match occurs if ball \(m\) is the \(m\)-th ball selected. The limit of this probability as \(n\) approaches infinity is required.

The probability of at least one match is given by \(1\) minus the probability of no matches (a derangement). The number of derangements of \(n\) objects is \(!n = n! \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{(-1)^k}{k!}\), so the probability of no matches is \(\frac{!n}{n!} = \sum_{k=0}^{n} \frac{(-1)^k}{k!}\). As \(n \to \infty\), this sum converges to \(e^{-1}\), the reciprocal of Euler's number.

Thus, the probability of no matches approaches \(\frac{1}{e} \approx 0.367879\). Therefore, the probability of at least one match approaches \(1 - \frac{1}{e} \approx 1 - 0.367879 = 0.632121\).

