Solution: The first ionization energy of \(\mathrm{H}_2\) is calculated using the dissociation energies and the atomic ionization energy of hydrogen. The dissociation energy \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2) = 4.478 \, \mathrm{eV}\) and \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^{+}) = 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}\) are given. The atomic ionization energy of hydrogen, \(\mathrm{IE_H}\), is \(13.598 \, \mathrm{eV}\).

